<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="17" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="18.[192,1440,1057,1242]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,372,1057,1081]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Distribution.</emphasis>
The species is known only from 
<collectingRegion box="[784,874,1058,1082]" country="United States of America" name="Florida" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Florida</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[938,1011,1058,1081]" country="United States of America" name="Texas" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Texas</collectingRegion>
in the 
<collectingCountry box="[1103,1276,1058,1082]" name="United States of America" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">United States</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[1294,1384,1058,1082]" captionStart="Figure 22" captionStartId="31.[192,276,1827,1849]" captionTargetBox="[192,1440,192,1718]" captionTargetId="figure-20@31.[192,1440,192,1091]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="Figure 22. North American distribution of Lionothus bidentatus (black circles), L. exiguus (black triangles), L. parvoculus (black squares)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5193732" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5193732/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
). Its distribution in the extreme south of 
<collectingRegion box="[653,726,1090,1113]" country="United States of America" name="Texas" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Texas</collectingRegion>
suggests that the species may also occur in 
<collectingCountry box="[1289,1379,1090,1114]" name="Mexico" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Mexico</collectingCountry>
. The Florida populations seem to be disjunct from those in Texas. They may have once been connected across the Gulf Coastal Plain at times of Pleistocene low sea levels. This was a route from a western source for faunas moving into Florida, and is recognized for the movement of both vertebrates (
<bibRefCitation author="Webb, S. D." bookContentInfo="765 p." box="[1293,1432,1186,1210]" editor="R. L. Myers &amp; J. J. Ewel" journalOrPublisher="University of Central Florida Press; Orlando, FL" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" pagination="70 - 100" refId="ref19300" refString="Webb, S. D. 1990. Historical biogeography. p. 70 - 100. In: R. L. Myers and J. J. Ewel (eds.). Ecosystems of Florida. University of Central Florida Press; Orlando, FL. 765 p." title="Historical biogeography" type="book chapter" volumeTitle="Ecosystems of Florida" year="1990">Webb 1990</bibRefCitation>
) and arthropods (
<bibRefCitation author="Deyrup, M. A." box="[396,559,1218,1242]" journalOrPublisher="Florida Scientist" pageId="18" pageNumber="17" pagination="254 - 271" part="52" refId="ref18206" refString="Deyrup, M. A. 1989. Arthropods endemic to Florida scrub. Florida Scientist 52: 254 - 271." title="Arthropods endemic to Florida scrub" type="journal article" year="1989">Deyrup 1989</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[192,1111,1281,1306]" box="[192,1111,1281,1306]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,360,1281,1305]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Seasonality.</emphasis>
Adults are known only from the months of March to August.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[192,1440,1345,1402]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,345,1345,1369]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Bionomics.</emphasis>
Adults are known from mesic forests, thorn thicket, and palm forest, often on sandy soils. All were collected in flight intercept traps.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
